  {
    "id": "knpc2021-q044",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "programming",
    "subtopic": "cpp-loops",
    "stem": "How many times will the loop be executed?",
    "stemCode": "int x=0;\nwhile (x<=1 && x>=10)\n{}",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Will be true indefinitely",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Will be true 5 times",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Will never happen",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "referenceUrl": "https://www.onlinegdb.com/online_c++_compiler",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2021,
      "originalNumber": 44
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "2b72e6991d986b3cea4b5e61c5d9d7f8c5bcbee2",
    "explanation": "The body never runs, so C. The condition x<=1 && x>=10 requires x to be both at most 1 and at least 10 at the same time, which no value satisfies, so the while test fails on the first evaluation and the loop executes zero times. The trap is misreading && as ||, where x=0 would satisfy x<=1 and loop forever."
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2018-q001",
    "type": "short_answer",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "fsm",
    "stem": "Mealy and Moore FSM depend on?",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "- Mealy FSM depends on present state and present input\n- Moore FSM depends on present state only",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2018,
      "originalNumber": 1
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "fef4effdb3da745be1dba0dc24915d94d6630ef5",
    "explanation": "A Mealy machine's output is a function of the present state AND the present inputs, so its output can change as soon as the input changes, within the clock cycle. A Moore machine's output is a function of the present state only, so it changes only after a clock edge. Consequence: Mealy usually needs fewer states and reacts one cycle earlier, but its output is more prone to glitches."
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2018-q004",
    "type": "short_answer",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "flip-flops",
    "stem": "Given this truth table, which flip flop is it?",
    "stemFigure": "/figures/knpc2018-q004.png",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "JK Flip Flop",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2018,
      "originalNumber": 4
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "a61f1883d9533f6d9187e8031c3028f870804778",
    "explanation": "The truth table shows JK = 00 hold (Q stays), 01 reset (Q = 0), 10 set (Q = 1) and 11 toggle (Q = Q'), which is the JK flip-flop. The giveaway is the 11 row: an SR flip-flop treats 11 as invalid/forbidden, while JK defines it as a toggle."
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2018-q005",
    "type": "short_answer",
    "topic": "data-structures-algorithms",
    "subtopic": "binary-search-tree",
    "stem": "What is the best time complexity of a Binary Search Tree algorithm?",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "O(logn)",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2018,
      "originalNumber": 5
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "2a8f8fd7d06a5b4b361950d4ff09f1fc7e086bbe",
    "explanation": "Search, insert and delete in a BST follow a single root-to-leaf path with one comparison per level, so the cost is proportional to the height. In the best (balanced) case the height is log2(n), giving O(log n). The classic trap: a BST built from already sorted input degenerates into a linked list of height n, so the worst case is O(n)."
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2018-q007",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "memory-management",
    "stem": "Which address is generated by the CPU?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Physical",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Virtual",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2018,
      "originalNumber": 7
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "8648c1caed8e27fb74e16f490bd5823fcc8977f5",
    "explanation": "The CPU only ever emits logical (virtual) addresses; the MMU translates them at run time into physical addresses on the memory bus. Physical is the trap: it is what memory sees, not what the CPU generates."
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2018-q009",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "process-states",
    "stem": "Which is a state that cannot occur in a process",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Blocked → Running",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Blocked → Ready",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Ready → Running",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Running → Blocked",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2018,
      "originalNumber": 9
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "d165396030768b381953a6b8b14ed32e501b677a",
    "explanation": "Blocked -> Running is illegal: a process waiting on I/O must first be moved to Ready when the event completes, and only the dispatcher can move a process from Ready to Running. The other three (Blocked -> Ready on I/O completion, Ready -> Running on dispatch, Running -> Blocked on an I/O request) are all standard transitions."
  },
